    "summary": "Shulgi was the second king of the [[event:1724|Third Dynasty of Ur]], reigning from approximately 2094 to 2047 BC, and is widely regarded as the most important ruler of the Ur III period. During his nearly half-century reign, Shulgi transformed the Ur III state from a regional power into a highly centralized bureaucratic empire. He standardized weights and measures across Mesopotamia, reformed the scribal curriculum, established a royal courier system, and reorganized the army, creating administrative structures that shaped Mesopotamian governance for generations.\n\nShulgi was also notable for his self-promotion as a divine king, proclaiming his own deification during his lifetime — an unusual act in Mesopotamian tradition. Royal hymns composed in his honor celebrated his physical prowess, his mastery of music and literacy, and his athletic achievements, including a legendary long-distance run. His reign produced an enormous volume of administrative tablets that illuminate the inner workings of one of the ancient world's most sophisticated bureaucratic states. Shulgi's legacy endured long after the empire's fall, as his administrative and cultural innovations left a deep imprint on subsequent Mesopotamian civilizations.",
